<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,822,2035]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1830,1855]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName box="[322,499,1830,1855]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hishimonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viraktamathi">
<emphasis box="[322,499,1830,1855]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">H. viraktamathi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
closely resembles 
<taxonomicName box="[713,829,1830,1855]" class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hishimonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="indicus">
<emphasis box="[713,829,1830,1855]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">H. indicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The closely opposed, long narrow basal processes of the aedeagus with a row of small widely spaced teeth along the distal half of the lateral surface distinguish 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Cicadellidae" genus="Hishimonus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="viraktamathi">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">H. viraktamathi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the latter.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="15.[151,1436,822,2035]" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">
This species breeds on 
<taxonomicName authority="(Roxb.) Wight &amp; Arn." authorityName="(Roxb.) Wight &amp; Arn." box="[458,917,1938,1963]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Combretaceae" genus="Terminalia" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="arjuna">
<emphasis box="[458,662,1938,1963]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Terminalia arjuna</emphasis>
(Roxb.) Wight &amp; Arn.
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName box="[931,1095,1938,1963]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Combretaceae" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="family">Combretaceae</taxonomicName>
) during monsoon season (July to September). The nymphs and adults are gregarious and are attended by the ant, 
<taxonomicName authority="Fabricius" authorityName="Fabricius" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Combretaceae" genus="Campnotus" kingdom="Plantae" order="Myrtales" pageId="15" pageNumber="116" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="compressus">
<emphasis box="[1165,1436,1975,1998]" italics="true" pageId="15" pageNumber="116">Campnotus compressus</emphasis>
(Fabricius)
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
